Introduction¶

Gapminder has collected a lot of information about how people live their lives in different countries, tracked across the years, and on a number of different indicators. The data set for this project comprises Education, Health, and Income data across all countries and categorized by regions (Europe, North America, South America, Central America, Middle East, Asia, Oceania)

def create_hist_subplot(nrows, df, bins, yLabel, title, edgeColor):
    hist_sp = plt.subplot(nrows)
    hist_sp.set_title(title)
    plt.hist(df, bins, range=(5, 95), edgecolor='black')
    plt.ylabel(yLabel)
    plt.show()

def create_bar_chart(xRange, labels, bar_height, rotation, bar_title, yLabel):
    plt.bar(xRange, bar_height)
    plt.xticks(xRange, labels, rotation='vertical')
    plt.title(bar_title)
    plt.ylabel(yLabel)
    plt.show()

Data Wrangling¶

Gapminder Data Process Steps¶

Step 1 - Load each Gapminder file into its own dataframe

A new column called region was added to the Gapminder Excel files which is used to classify the countries in the file to a specific region.

Step 2 - Reshape each dataframe

The pandas melt function is used to convert the columns of each data frame into rows which get stored into new data frames. The new data frame column layout is: country, year, region, [Gapminder data category].

An example is country, year, region, TotalGDP_USD. The TotalGDP_USD is a derived column populated from the Gapminder data values in the source dataframe. Each new data frame will have its own unique derived column based on which source dataframe it was created from. The new dataframes are named with a suffix of "_byRow".

Step 3 - Remove records containing NAN/null values

Step 4 - Merge the new dataframes (suffixed with "_byRow") into one dataframe

The new dataframe is called [Regions]_Dataset. It is saved to a CSV file to be used in the data exploration phase.

Gapminder data files

There are seven Gapminder data files representing different categories of demographic data. Below are links to each file load section¶

  1. Load Total GDP file
  2. Load Life Expectancy in years file
  3. Load GDP per capita file
  4. Load Sucide total deaths file
  5. Load Mean school years men 25 to 34
  6. Load Mean school years women 25 to 34
  7. Basic water access percent

Regions

There are eight regions defined. The regions are:¶

  1. Africa
  2. Asia
  3. Europe
  4. Middle East
  5. North America
  6. South America
  7. Central America
  8. Oceania

Data Cleaning¶

Data structure and Data issues¶

The dataframes have four columns: country; Region; year; and Gapminder category which is one of the seven categories mentioned earlier. The issues found are that some dataframes have data for historical years dating back as far as 1800 while other dataframes do not have data going back that far. Also, every dataframe across all Gapminder data categories have missing values. The first step is to remove all records from every dataframe with null values. The second step is to merge the dataframes into one single dataframe. The type of join operation will be an "inner join" which means that every dataframe must have matching records for country, Region, and year to be included into the final dataframe.

Step 1: Remove rows for any column with NAN / null values¶

Conclusions¶

Does overall basic water access increase GDP per capita?¶

In both 2009 and 2014, outliers were identified as countries that had 100% overall access to basic water services. These countries were the United States and Canada in the North America region. This Region was excluded from the data set because we are interested in seeing incremental changes in overall basic water access over a five year period and its impact on GDP per capita.

In 2009, there are countries with 90 percent or higher overall access to basic water services with varying GDP per capita. This may indicate that in 2009, these countries GDP per capita did not correlate to overall basic water access percentage. However in 2014, we see a stronger relationship between overall basic water access percent and GDP per capita. There is more analysis needed to try and explain this improved relationship. First, there could of been technological advances in access to water made since 2009. It will also be of interest to isolate which countries show the stronger corrlation in 2014 and where they appeared in the 2005 scatter plot. The data set for overall basic water access is limited as it only dates back to year 2000. As more data is collected in the future, it will be interesting to see whehter this relationship gets stronger, weaker or remains the same.

Do women in school between ages 25 to 34 increase life expectancy?¶

There are two scatter plots created 10 years apart, 2005 and 2014. The data sets for 2005 and 2014 were restricted where the average number of women attending school is greater than or equal to one.

In both plots for 2005 and 2014, we see a correlation between the average number of years spent in school for women ages 25 to 34 and life expectancy. The next steps would be to identify which regions/countries in the world have the strongest correlation, and why.

Do men in school between ages 25 to 34 increase life expectancy?¶

The same filter was applied as for women in that only average values greater than or equal to 1 year in school for men were used. Both 2005 and 2014 plots show a relationship between adult men ages 25 to 34 attending school and increased life expectancy. We see life expectancy rising to 80 and above when the average number of men attending school rises above 12. Again, it would be interesting to see if this relationship exists among all regions in the world or not.

Do countries with low life expectencies see higher number of suicide deaths?¶

There were two filters applied to the 2005 dataset, include life expectancies above 9 years and eliminate China and India. Both China and India had very large number of suicide deaths which would have skewed the plots if included. Even with these adjustments, there is still appears to be no relationship between these two variables

Does increase in Life Expectancy contribute to higher Total GDP?¶

The North America region was excluded from this data set as it had Total GDP that was much larger than all other regions. But there appears to be little relationship between these two variables. There is a slight variation in Total GDP when life expectancy reaches 80. This could imply that Total GDP is driven by the working class people whom are under age 65. We cannot draw this conclusion without looking at data for the working class population.
